In a community where women’s roles are traditionally limited, this can be a very difficult step for her. But nevertheless, women in the various camps of the Sahrawi population demand a special role in maintaining the family’s financial security.

Studies by the Women’s Commission for Refugee Women and Children support this assertion and prove that 80% of the men do not want to marry women from refugee camps.

Men wishing to obtain a spouse raise enough money to pay compensation to alienated families. If they fail to pay the ransom, degenerate pressure is used to marry the woman, for example by forcing it into prostitution.

Polygamy is the norm. When a woman has financial problems, another man may marry her in order to pay the penalty.

The Islamization of Western Sahara

The calm town of Smara in Tindouf camps, Algeria, is a small town with a population averaging 25,000 residents. The town is a market center with its attractive dominant men and fervent believers. The main street of the town is lined with several mosques. Most of these depend to the Hutus — Wahhabi movement of the Ulema or La Kuruma.
